				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Shiru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">mikejmoffitt wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'm worried that someone is actually going to start their game with the message, &quot;Please rotate your television by ninety degrees!&quot;</div><br />In fact there were such games in the past, I recall an arcade shooter port for PS1. Luckily, is was optional - either you see the narrow window, of fullscreen, but has to turn the TV 90 degree.</div><br /><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jmHBIe6uv9k" class="postlink">Ikaruga does this</a> and is a game available for fairly newish consoles (PS2, GC, DC, as well as Xbox360).  The first time I saw the option in the config menu I literally said &quot;What the fuck?  They can't be serious...&quot;<br /><br />BTW, haven't read the rest of the thread, and I did laugh at the initial proposal ( :-) ), but rotating a CRT monitor isn't a wise idea anyway unless you can degauss it shortly after -- by rotating it it messes up the magnetisation aspect, often resulting in discolouration (sometimes the damage can be permanent).  <a href="http://www.repairfaq.org/samnew/tvfaq/tvtiltpic.htm" class="postlink">Nope I'm not crazy</a>.  This is one of the many reasons why arcade cabinets with CRT rotation support have degauss buttons (I own a CANDY 25 cab and had a Taito Egret cab as well, so I'm aware of the importance of degaussing).<br /><br />If I remember right, there were also reasons to try and have your CRT always facing some particular direction -- had to do with north vs. south pole alignment -- and if you ever changed it (i.e. if it was previously facing north but was relocated and now faces east) you were supposed to degauss it.<br /><br />Obviously this complexity doesn't apply to LCDs.</div>

