						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Shiru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I don't remember much about CRT these days, but isn't every CRT TV has a built-in degaussing coil and automatic degauss circuit?</div><br />The last CRT TV I had access to was in 2003 and it did not have a degaussing coil.  Some CRT computer monitors, such as many models of Sony Trinitrons (very popular in the 90s), definitely had both -- most of the ones I'd used or seen would degauss on power-up (you could tell because of the &quot;thwong&quot; noise they'd make).  But I've never seen a television that did that.  Of course, this comes from a guy who has owned 4&quot;, 9&quot;, and 13&quot; TVs, so I'm probably not a very good candidate to make an authoritative statement.<br /><br />However, I do remember a few friends of mine having larger TVs (30&quot;) back in the mid-90s which after being exposed to badly-shielded home stereo speakers (i.e. magnets) had to be degaussed manually due to massive discolouration and warping along the sides of the CRT.  Power-cycling did nothing and there was no degauss button.  Luckily a fellow student had a degaussing coil and would either loan it to people he trusted or would just go to their houses to degauss their TVs.</div>

