					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The LCD dead/lit pixel issue and how manufacturers justify it still chaps my ass to this day -- <strong>the entire point of a monitor/display is to show all the visual data (pixel) sent to it across the wire</strong>.</div><br />Even a color CRT doesn't do that. Dot pitch, etc.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And don't get me started on the fuckwadery that is <a href="http://www.anandtech.com/show/6482/lg-29ea93-ultrawide-display-missing-its-target" class="postlink">shit like this</a>.</div><br />I don't see how a 2560x1080 monitor is necessarily fornicationwadery. To me, it looks like something intended to replace a pair of 1280x1024 panels, and window managers have for years included a &quot;Snap&quot; or &quot;Tile&quot; feature to make good use of this space. It has the advantage of a dual monitor without an annoying pair of bezels down the middle.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The only LCD displays I've seen that are utterly amazing are the ones used in Vewlix arcade cabinets -- which you practically have to take out a bank loan to afford.</div><br />Businesses can afford loans.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">While I'm ranting I am absolutely sick and ired of the 1080 pixel fixation that has no justification whatsoever (I repeat: <strong>no justification</strong>.</div><br />I can think of two justifications. One is economies of scale: they make these panels on the same assembly line as the TV. The other is that 1920x1080 is big enough for two 8.5x11 inch pages at 96 dpi (1632x1056).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And don't get me started on the fact that DPI on desktop displays is utter shit compared to things like handheld devices, and again, for no justified reason.</div><br />The reason here is that applications that aren't retina-aware tend to produce incorrect displays when the PC's effective DPI is set above 96.</div>

